      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A thousand apologies! My mind, bless its chaotic, goblin-infested little depths, just keeps spiraling back to the tiny, mischievous creatures. Don't worry, I'll try to keep the green-skinned little scavengers out of the main explanation, though it's frankly quite hard when talking about lost *stuff*. When inventory shrinkage occurs, it’s basically like a surge group of goblins sneaking into your warehouse overnight and carting off perfectly good widgets.\n\nThe base Inventory Turnover Formula is $\\text{COGS} / \\text{Average Inventory}$. To show the *real* impact, you must quantify that shrinkage loss—let’s call it $\\text{Shrinkage Value}$. You can either increase your COGS by the $\\text{Shrinkage Value}$ (because you effectively had to replace it anyway) or, alternatively, decrease your Average Inventory by that same lost amount. The latter often gives a more conservative—and perhaps more terrifyingly honest—picture of how much real stock you actually moved.",
